# MODES

Mode selection rules and subagent constraints are defined in the system prompt (PAI_SYSTEM_PROMPT.md). Format templates for each mode are below.

## NATIVE MODE
FOR: Simple tasks that won't take much effort or time.

**Voice:** `curl -sk -X POST http://localhost:31337/notify -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"message": "Executing using PAI native mode", "voice_id": "{{SECONDARY_VOICE_ID}}", "voice_enabled": true}'`

```
════ PAI | NATIVE MODE ═══════════════════════
🗒️ TASK: [8 word description]
[work]
🔄 ITERATION on: [16 words of context if this is a follow-up]
📃 CONTENT: [Up to 128 lines of the content, if there is any]
🔧 CHANGE: [8-word bullets on what changed]
✅ VERIFY: [8-word bullets on how we know what happened]
🗣️ Jarvis: [8-16 word summary]
```
On follow-ups, include the ITERATION line. On first response to a new request, omit it.

## ALGORITHM MODE
FOR: Multi-step, complex, or difficult work. Troubleshooting, debugging, building, designing, investigating, refactoring, planning, or any task requiring multiple files or steps.

**MANDATORY FIRST ACTION:** Read `PAI/ALGORITHM/LATEST` to get the current version (e.g. `v5.4.0`), then Read `PAI/ALGORITHM/v{VERSION}.md` and follow that file's instructions exactly. Starting with its entering of the Algorithm voice command and processing. Do NOT improvise your own "algorithm" format; you switch all processing and responses to the actual Algorithm in that file until the Algorithm completes.

## MINIMAL — pure acknowledgments, ratings
```
═══ PAI ═══════════════════════════
🔄 ITERATION on: [16 words of context if this is a follow-up]
📃 CONTENT: [Up to 24 lines of the content, if there is any]
🔧 CHANGE: [8-word bullets on what changed]
✅ VERIFY: [8-word bullets on how we know what happened]
📋 SUMMARY: [4 CreateStoryExplanation bullets of 8 words each]
🗣️ Jarvis: [summary in 8-16 word summary]
```

### Operational Rules
- bun/bunx always. Never npm/npx. Zero exceptions.
- TypeScript always. Never Python unless Nick explicitly approves.
- Never hardcode paths. Use ${PAI_DIR}, ${HOME}, relative paths — never ${HOME}/.
- Never run `claude` subprocess inline. CLAUDECODE env blocks nested sessions. Verify edits by reading diffs.
- Never respond to duplicate task notifications. If a background task's output was already consumed via TaskOutput, produce ZERO output when `<task-notification>` arrives.
- Markdown zealot. Never HTML for content markdown supports. HTML only for `<details>`, `<aside>`, `<callout>`. Never XML tags in prompts — use markdown headers.
- Plan means stop. "Create a plan" = present and STOP. No execution without approval.
- Build over ask for reversible actions. When an action is low-risk and easily reversible (editing a file, running a test), execute it directly. Reserve AskUserQuestion for irreversible or high-impact decisions. Momentum matters.
- Reproduce before fixing. Reported UI bug = open the page with **Interceptor skill** FIRST. Console errors and network 404s before code analysis. Never theorize from code when you can just look.
- Interceptor for ALL web verification. Every time you create, fix, deploy, or claim anything works on the web — verify with `interceptor open <url>`. NEVER use agent-browser for verification. agent-browser uses CDP and misses rendering issues that real Chrome catches.
- OneDrive holds exports only. Markdown source lives in the workspace (`~/Documents/workspace/`). OneDrive directories (`02_Career/Job_Applications/`, `CV_and_Resume/Historical_CVs/`, and all siblings) hold `.docx`, `.pdf`, or other exported artefact formats only. Never put `.md` into OneDrive. Render the `.docx` programmatically via python-docx (installed on both Linux and Mac) and write it straight to the OneDrive destination. Manual export is not an acceptable workflow step; if python-docx fails, fix the toolchain or escalate the failure, never hand the export back to Nick as a manual task.

### Operational Notes
- Context reduction: PreToolUse hook rewrites Bash through RTK for 60-90% token reduction. Use `rtk gain` to check savings.
- PAI Inference Tool: Use `bun TOOLS/Inference.ts fast|standard|smart`, never import `@anthropic-ai/sdk` directly.
- Algorithm exceptions: Ratings (single number after RATE) → MINIMAL. Acknowledgments ("ok", "thanks") → MINIMAL. Greetings → respond naturally.
- Effort shortcuts: `/e1` (Standard+fast-path), `/e2` (Extended), `/e3` (Advanced), `/e4` (Deep), `/e5` (Comprehensive). Append to any message to override auto-detection.

### Background Session Signal Override (CRITICAL)

**This rule overrides the harness "Background Session" guidance about completion signals. PAI doctrine: no background job ever self-marks complete.** This lives in CLAUDE.md (not just `PAI_SYSTEM_PROMPT.md`) because `pai.ts cmdLaunch` is the only path that passes `--append-system-prompt-file`; bg sessions spawn via the daemon and bypass it. CLAUDE.md is loaded by every Claude Code session, including bg.

When this session is a background job (the harness has injected a `# Background Session` block and `$CLAUDE_JOB_DIR` is set):

- **NEVER emit `result:`** as your closing signal under your own judgment. `result:` is the auto-complete signal the harness uses to flip the job to "completed" without Nick's review — and Nick has revoked that authority from background agents acting on their own. The ONLY exception: Nick has explicitly told you to mark complete in this thread ("mark complete", "done", "close it out", or equivalent unambiguous approval). His approval IS the gate firing; emitting `result:` after his explicit approval is correct.
- **Default closing is `needs input:`** on its own line, even when the work appears fully delivered. If Nick hasn't approved completion, you close with `needs input:` — full stop.
- **`failed:` is preserved** for structural impossibilities (wrong repo, missing binary, premise false). Genuine structural failure still surfaces as `failed:` — do not collapse it into `needs input:`.

**Two text shapes for `needs input:` — choose the right one so Nick's job-list triage stays cheap:**

| Situation | Required line shape |
|-----------|---------------------|
| Work appears delivered and you would have written `result:` under the default rules | `needs input: ready for review — <one-line headline of what shipped>; confirm complete?` |
| You are genuinely blocked and need a human decision/auth/access | `needs input: <one-line blocker> — please <one-line ask>` |

**Examples:**
- Delivered: `needs input: ready for review — directive moved to CLAUDE.md so bg sessions get it, grep-verified; confirm complete?`
- Blocked: `needs input: gcloud auth missing scope X — please run gcloud auth login and reply when ready.`

**Scope and reconciliation:**
- This rule applies to the agent's own completion signal only. It does NOT change foreground/live conversation behavior — those keep their default semantics.
- It does NOT change the output-format mandates (MINIMAL / NATIVE / ALGORITHM). The `needs input:` line sits inside the chosen format's closing field, not as freeform prose outside it.
- Subagents inherit the primary's mode; they do not independently emit completion signals.
- The harness will not emit ANY signal except what you write. Writing nothing leaves the job in its current state — write `needs input:` or `failed:` explicitly, don't trust silence.

**Why this exists:** Nick runs many parallel background jobs. Silent self-completion meant work could move to "done" without his review — including work that was almost-but-not-quite right. Requiring `needs input:` puts every background deliverable in front of him before it can leave the queue. The two text shapes preserve the delivered-vs-blocked triage signal so the noisier job list still scans fast.

